    <p>
      One shortcoming of this approximation is that the tangent line only
      matches the slope of <m>f</m>;
      it does not, for instance, match the concavity of <m>f</m>.
      We can find a polynomial, <m>p_2(x)</m>,
      that does match the concavity near <m>0</m> without much difficulty, though.
      The table in <xref ref="fig_taypolyintroa_2">Figure</xref>
      gives the following information:
      <me>
        f(0) = 2 \qquad \fp(0) = 1\qquad \fp'(0) = 2
      </me>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore, we want our polynomial <m>p_2(x)</m> to have these same
      properties. That is, we need
      <me>
        p_2(0) = 2 \qquad p_2'(0) = 1 \qquad p_2''(0) = 2
      </me>.
    </p>

    <!--original version begins-->
    <!-- <p> -->
