    <!-- </p> -->
    <!--original version ends-->

    <!--early version begins-->
    <p>
      Let's start with a general quadratic function
      <me>
        p(x) = a_0+a_1x+a_2x^2
      </me>.
      We find the following:
      <md>
        <mrow>p_2(x) \amp = a_0+a_1x+a_2x^2 \amp p_2(0)\amp=a_0</mrow>
        <mrow>p_2\primeskip '(x) \amp = a_1+2a_2x\amp p_2\primeskip '(0) \amp = a_1</mrow>
        <mrow>p_2\primeskip ''(x) \amp = 2a_2 \amp p_2\primeskip''(0) \amp = 2a_2</mrow>
      </md>.
      To get the desired properties above, we must have
      <me>
        a_0 = f(0) = 2,\, a_1 = \fp(0) = 1,\, 2a_2 = \fpp(0) = 2
      </me>,
      so <m>a_0=2</m>, <m>a_1=1</m>, and <m>a_2 = 2/2=1</m>, giving us the polynomial
      <me>
        p_2(x) = 2+x+x^2.
      </me>
    </p>
      <!--early version ends-->

    <p>
      We can repeat this approximation process by creating polynomials of
      higher degree that match more of the derivatives of <m>f</m> at <m>x=0</m>.
      In general, a polynomial of degree <m>n</m> can be created to match the
      first <m>n</m> derivatives of <m>f</m>.
      <xref ref="fig_taypolyintrob">Figure</xref>
      shows <m>p_4(x)= -x^4/2-x^3/6+x^2+x+2</m>,
      whose first four derivatives at 0 match those of <m>f</m>.
      <!--original version begins-->
      <!-- (Using the table in <xref ref="fig_taypolyintroa_2">Figure</xref>, -->
      <!-- start with <m>p_4^{(4)}(x)=-12</m> and solve the related initial-value problem.) -->
      <!--original version ends-->
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig_taypolyintrob">
