    <example xml:id="ex_taypoly6">
      <title>Approximating an unknown function</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A function <m>y=f(x)</m> is unknown save for the following two facts.

          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>y(0) = f(0) = 1</m>, and
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>y'= y^2</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>

        <p>
          (This second fact says that amazingly,
          the derivative of the function is actually the function squared!)
        </p>

        <p>
          Find the degree 3 Maclaurin polynomial <m>p_3(x)</m> of <m>y=f(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          One might initially think that not enough information is given to
          find <m>p_3(x)</m>.
          However, note how the second fact above actually lets us know what
          <m>y'(0)</m> is:
          <me>
            y' = y^2 \Rightarrow y'(0) = y^2(0)
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Since <m>y(0) = 1</m>, we conclude that <m>y'(0) = 1</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Now we find information about <m>y''</m>.
          Starting with <m>y'=y^2</m>,
          take derivatives of both sides,
          <em>with respect to <m>x</m></em>.
          That means we must use implicit differentiation.
          <md>
            <mrow>y' \amp = y^2</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{d}{dx}\big(y'\big) \amp = \frac{d}{dx}\big(y^2\big)</mrow>
            <mrow>y'' \amp = 2y\cdot y'.</mrow>
            <intertext>Now evaluate both sides at <m>x=0</m>:</intertext>
            <mrow>y''(0) \amp = 2y(0)\cdot y'(0)</mrow>
            <mrow>y''(0) \amp = 2</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>

        <p>
          We repeat this once more to find <m>y'''(0)</m>.
          We again use implicit differentiation;
          this time the Product Rule is also required.
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{d}{dx}\big(y''\big) \amp = \frac{d}{dx} \big(2yy'\big)</mrow>
            <mrow>y''' \amp = 2y'\cdot y' + 2y\cdot y''.</mrow>
            <intertext>Now evaluate both sides at <m>x=0</m>:</intertext>
            <mrow>y'''(0) \amp = 2y'(0)^2 + 2y(0)y''(0)</mrow>
            <mrow>y'''(0) \amp =  2+4=6</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>

        <p>
          In summary, we have:
          <me>
            y(0) = 1 \qquad y'(0) = 1  \qquad y''(0) = 2 \qquad y'''(0) = 6
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p>
          We can now form <m>p_3(x)</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>p_3(x) \amp = 1 + x + \frac{2}{2!}x^2 + \frac{6}{3!}x^3</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = 1+x+x^2+x^3</mrow>
          </md>.
  <!--ToDo: the next comment was added during last conversion. Not quite accurare, as Taylor series come next. Maybe it meant to refer to geometric series?-->
<!--          In general, it appears that <m>p_n(x)=1+x+x^2+x^3+\dots +x^n</m>,-->
 <!--         which we have seen before is equivalent to <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{1-x}</m> on <m>(-1,1)</m>.-->
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig_taypoly6">
          <caption>A graph of <m>y=-1/(x-1)</m> and <m>y=p_3(x)</m> from
          <xref ref="ex_taypoly6">Example</xref></caption>
          <!-- START figures/fig_taypoly6.tex -->
          <image xml:id="img_taypoly6" width="47%">
            <description></description>
            <latex-image>

          \begin{tikzpicture}

          \begin{axis}[
          ymin=-.1,ymax=3.5,
          xmin=-1.1,xmax=1.4
          ]

          \addplot+ [domain=-1:.65,samples=40] {-1/(x-1)} node[pos=1,left]{\scriptsize $\displaystyle y= \frac{1}{1-x}$};
          \addplot+ [domain=-1:0.81,samples=40] {1+x+x^2+x^3} node [pos=1, below right]{\scriptsize $y=p_3(x)$};

          \end{axis}

          \end{tikzpicture}

            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <!-- figures/fig_taypoly6.tex END -->
        </figure>

        <p>
          It turns out that the differential equation we started with,
          <m>y'=y^2</m>,
          where <m>y(0)=1</m>, can be solved without too much difficulty:
          <me>y = \frac{1}{1-x}</me>.
          <xref ref="fig_taypoly6">Figure</xref>
          shows this function plotted with <m>p_3(x)</m>.
          Note how similar they are near <m>x=0</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      It is beyond the scope of this text to pursue error analysis when using
      Taylor polynomials to approximate solutions to differential equations.
      This topic is often broached in introductory Differential Equations
      courses and usually covered in depth in Numerical Analysis courses.
      Such an analysis is very important;
      one needs to know how good their approximation is.
      We explored this example simply to demonstrate the usefulness of Taylor
      polynomials.
    </p>

